    [15:29:43] [W1] ⚖️ JUDGED: team_a | The sealing (ἐσφραγίσθητε εἰς ἡμέραν ἀπολυτρώσεως) functions as a declaration of God's genuine purpose and provision for the believers, with εἰς operating telically (as in 1:14), not as an unconditional guarantee that structurally excludes the possibility of the recipients falling under the judgment of 5:5-6. The imperatives (μὴ λυπεῖτε, 4:30) carry real soteriological consequences, as the unanimous patristic tradition on Ef 5:5-6 confirms (Chrysostom, Ambrosiaster, Jerome, Aquinas, Cyprian, Irenaeus all read genuine warning with real consequences). The 'third option' (imperatives as guaranteed means of divine fulfillment) is logically coherent in the abstract but does not adequately explain: (1) Chrysostom's explicit statement that some who received the light have extinguished it (id=22531); (2) the ἵνα δυνηθῆτε of 6:13 which presupposes contingency; (3) the identification by Chrysostom (id=248908) of the κενοὶ λόγοι as precisely the position that says the warnings are 'impossible' or 'hyperbolic.' Both positions are logically coherent, but the telic-conditional reading better integrates the totality of evidence internal to Ephesians and the patristic exegesis directly on the passage in question.
